time_all = read.csv("../../time.csv")
N = 20000
time = head(time_all, N)
head(time)

The temporal dynamics of all timers must be accounted for. They all seem to warm up for a long time.

plot(NULL, xlim=c(1, N), ylim=c(0, 3000))
lines(time$clock_gettime, type = "l", col = "red")
lines(time$time, type = "l", col = "blue")
lines(time$runtime_nano, type = "l", col = "green")

plot(NULL, xlim=c(1, N), ylim=c(1, 3.5))
par(ylog=TRUE)
lines(time$clock_gettime, type = "l", col = "red")
lines(time$time, type = "l", col = "blue")
lines(time$runtime_nano, type = "l", col = "green")

It seems runtimeNano is the most accurate and stable one. We could perhaps subtract the Min. of this from all the measurements

Summary:

  1. We should discard about 5000 first observations (TODO)
  2. It is probably a good idea to monitor and register the timer overhead during the opcode measurements (TODO).
  3. Due to periods of increased overhead, sometimes the measurements might be over-timed for several consecutive measurements. Should we discard all measurements where just time measurement is above a threshold? (TODO)
  4. runtimeNano is clearly the winner, but it still has high values quite often, and is subject to large overhead during warm-up and during the temporary increase periods
  5. We can also subtract the minimum observed timer overhead (Ive seen 21ns) of runtimeNano from all the measurements (TODO)
  6. Next step would be to consider subtracting more, considering its a justified move (TODO)
  7. Alternatively, we could do more in-depth analysis of the behaviors observed and try to normalize the timer readings more (TODO optional)
